{{Infobox museum | name = Seattle Asian Art Museum | image = Seattle Asian Art Museum.jpg | imagesize = 250 | caption = Front entrance of the building facing west | alt = | established = 1994 | location = [[Volunteer Park, Seattle|Volunteer Park]], [[Seattle]], Washington, United States | type = [[Art museum]] | collection = | visitors = | director = | president = | curator = | owner = [[City of Seattle]] | publictransit = | car_park = | network = | website = {{URL|http://www.seattleartmuseum.org/visit/asian-art-museum|Seattle Asian Art Museum}} | embedded = {{Infobox NRHP | name = Seattle Art Museum | nrhp_type = | embed = yes | image = | alt = | caption = | locmapin = Washington | map_alt = | map_caption = | map_width = 235 | coordinates = {{coord|47.6303|-122.3143|region:US-WA|display=inline,title}} | location = [[Seattle, Washington]] | built = 1933 | architect = [[Carl F. Gould]] | architecture = [[Art Moderne]] | added = July 20, 2016 | designated_nrhp_type = | refnum = 16000474<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2010a|dateform=mdy|accessdate=January 7, 2017}}</ref> | mpsub = | governing_body = | designated_other1 = Seattle Landmark | designated_other1_name = Seattle | designated_other1_date = June 21, 1989 }} }}
[[File:SAAM camel statue.jpg|thumb|Camel statue in front of the SAAM]] The '''Seattle Asian Art Museum''' ('''SAAM''') is a [[museum]] of [[History of Eastern art|Asian art]] located inside [[Volunteer Park, Seattle|Volunteer Park]] in the [[Capitol Hill, Seattle, Washington|Capitol Hill]] neighborhood of [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], [[United States]]. Part of the [[Seattle Art Museum]], the SAAM occupies the 1933 [[Art Deco]] building (designed by [[Carl F. Gould]] of the architectural firm [[Bebb and Gould]] and listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]]) which was originally home to the Seattle Art Museum's main collection. In 1991 the main collection moved to a newly constructed Seattle Art Museum building in [[Downtown, Seattle, Washington|downtown Seattle]]. The building in Volunteer Park remained closed until 1994, when it reopened as the Seattle Asian Art Museum.<ref>{{cite journal | editor1-last=Reynolds |editor1-first=Jonathan M. |date=September 1994 |title=Museum News |journal=Newsletter, East Asian Art and Archaeology |publisher=Center of Japanese Studies, University of Michigan |issue=47 |pages=13 }}</ref> Admission is free on the first Thursday and the first Saturday of every month.
==Building==
The Seattle Asian Art Museum is housed in a historic [[Art Deco]] building designed in 1933 by [[Carl F. Gould]] of the architectural firm [[Bebb and Gould]]. From 1933 to 1991, the building served as the home of the [[Seattle Art Museum]] and its main collection. After the main collection moved to a new museum in [[Downtown Seattle]], the building was renovated at a cost of $5.2 million.
The building was designated a [[List of Seattle landmarks|Seattle landmark]] in 1989 and added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2016.<ref>[https://www.cityofseattle.gov/neighborhoods/preservation/s.htm Landmarks Alphabetical Listing for S] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721033852/https://www.cityofseattle.gov/neighborhoods/preservation/s.htm |date=2011-07-21 }}, Individual Landmarks, Department of Neighborhoods, City of Seattle. Accessed December 28, 2007.</ref>
==History==
The Seattle Art Museum was founded in 1933 by Richard E. Fuller, a collector of Asian art. The museum announced in 1993 that it would open an Asian art museum at its former location in Volunteer Park.<ref>{{cite news |last=Updike |first=Robin |date=June 27, 1993 |title=Old SAM: A museum gets ready to be born again |page=F8 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19930627&slug=1708479 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=January 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Updike |first=Robin |date=July 31, 1994 |title=Honoring Asia's treasures: the rebirth of an art museum gives Seattle a long-awaited chance to savor its cultural legacy |page=M1 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref>
A reception at the museum was held on November 20, 1993 as part of the [[APEC]] Summit, attended by the leaders of East Asian nations and 400 guests.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gupta |first=Himanee |date=November 20, 1993 |title=Meeting to remember for Seattleites: guests thriled by rubbing shoulders with world leaders |page=A10 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> The museum opened to the public on August 13, 1994, during a ceremony attended by 6,000 visitors.<ref>{{cite news |last=Updike |first=Robin |date=August 13, 1994 |title=SAAM's showcase: today the public gets its look at Asian treasures |page=C1 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref>
The museum was closed in spring 2017 for a renovation and expansion program, scheduled to last until 2019.<ref>[http://www.seattleartmuseum.org/inspire SAM website]</ref>
